Continuous Time  Fourier Transform
==================================

Take an aperiodic function, prentend it is periodic.

$a_k=\frac{1}{T}\int_{<T>}x(t)e^{-j\omega_0 kt}dt$ (Analysis)

$X(j\omega)=\int_{-\infty}^{x(t)e^{j\omega t}dt}$ (Analysis)

$x(t)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{infty}$X(j\omega)e^{j\omega t}d\omega

$sinc(x)=\frac{\sin(\pi x)}{\pi x}$

Dirichlet Conditions
--------------------

For a fourier transform of x(t) to converge:

+ x(t) is absolutely integrable: $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|x(t)|dt<\infty$
+ x(t) has finite number of extrema in any finite interval
+ x(t) has finite number of discontinuities in any finite interval

Properties of Fourier Transforms
--------------------------------

$\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \delta(\omega-\omega_0)e^{j\omega t}d\omega=e^{j\omega_0 t}$

$X(jw)=2\pi \sum_{<k>} a_k \delta(\omega-k\omega_0)$

+ $ax+by$ <-ft-> $aX+bY$
+ $x(t-t_0)$ <-ft-> $e^{j\omega t_0}X(j\omega)$
+ $x*(t)$ <-ft-> $X*(-j\omega)$
+ $\frac{d}{dt}x(t)$ <-ft-> $j\omega X(j\omega)$
+ $x(at)$ <-ft-> $\frac{1}{|a|}X(j\frac{\omega}{a})$
	+ If $x(-t)=x(t)$, then $X(j\omega)=X(-j\omega)$
	+ If x(t) is also real, $X*(j\omega)=X(jw)$, or X is real.
+ Parseval's Relation $$
+ \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} |x(t)|^2 dt = \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} |X(j\omega)|^2 d\omega
